title-1:title_sort_portion: Official Provincial, Corporation, and Mayoralty Seals
abstract-1:abstract_value: Reproduction of photograph of 13 city, mayoralty, corporation, and provincial seals, dated from 1654 to 1915, presumably of various materials, including metal: [1] Seal of New Netherland, reproduction patented by Stuyvesant to Harck Syboutsen on April 18, 1664, owned by the N.Y. Title Guarantee and Trust Co; [2] The Stuyvesant seal, reproduction made from Governor Stuyvesant's ring owned by the New York Historical Society; [3] First city seal, dated 1654, reproduction made from either a deed dated January 21, 1656, from Abraham Verplanck to Rev. Johannes Megapolensis, or a certificate of citizenship dated December 20, 1659, to Cornelius Jansen van Hoorn; [4] First city seal, dated 1654, reproduction made from either a deed dated January 21, 1656, from Abraham Verplanck to Rev. Johannes Megapolensis, or a certificate of citizenship dated December 20, 1659, to Cornelius Jansen van Hoorn; [5] First English provincial seal brought by Lovelace, 1669, owned by the New York Public Library, reproduced from the Dongan Charter; [6] City seal, adopted 1686, reproduction from a land grant to Cornelis Van Ranst, dated February 12, 1750, owned by the New York Historical Society; [7] City seal in use as early as 1687, reproduction from a certificate of sale of windmill property to Jasper Nessepott, dated February 13, 1689, owned by the New York Historical Society; [8] City seal of 1686, owned by Mr. Frank Wessella Demarest, reproduced from a grant to Conraed Ten Eyck, dated September 1, 1687; [9] First mayoralty seal, adopted in 1735, owned by the New York Public Library (N.Y. City Papers, Mss Division), reproduced from a commission appointing R. Skaats to be inspector and receiver in the office of the clerk of the market, dated July 10, 1784; [10] City seal adopted in 1784, owned by the New York Historical Society, no. 3 of the Paulding Collection; [11] Mayoralty seal adopted in 1784, owned by the New York Historical Society, no. 6 of the Paulding Collection; [12] Mayoralty seal adopted in 1814; [13] City seal designed by Paul Manship in 1915, owned by the City of New York. All references can be found on page 18 of volume 6.

abstract-1:abstract_value:
Two images on the page. 

Top: Originally from The New-York Magazine; or, Literary Repository, August, 1794.

Bottom: The church depicted is the Dutch church at Harlem, the third church there, built in 1788 and taken down in 1825.

title-1:title_sort_portion: Map of the Original Grants and Farms
abstract-1:abstract_value: "The Map of Original Grants and Farms was designed to supplement the Map of the Dutch Grants." This map was prepared for publication in the volume, and lays out the Dutch ground-briefs and English patent prior to the Dongan charter of 1686. Dates inferred from 1891 date of the original Map of the Dutch Grants, for which this map was made as a supplement, and the 1928 date of the creator's signature. See Volume 6, page 67.

abstract-1:abstract_value:
Two images on the page.

Top: Originally from The New-York Magazine; or, Literary Repository, June 1790. This building was called Richmond Hill, and Vice-President John Adams resided there after the Revolution.

Bottom: The artist and engraver may have been John Scoles, 1772?-1853.

abstract-1:abstract_value:
Two images on the page. 

Top: The new Presbyterian Meeting, depicted here, was commonly called the Brick Church.

Bottom: The three buildings depicted are Bank of New York, New York Insurance Company, and a branch of the Bank of United States (32, 34, and 38 Wall Street)

title-1:title_sort_portion: "Freedom of the City," and Gold Box to Contain Seal, Presented to Andrew Hamilton, dated Sept. 29, 1735
abstract-1:abstract_value: Reproduction of photograph of manuscript on vellum, authored by the mayor of New York, Paul Richard, Esq., and the Recorder Alderman and Assistants of the City of New York, addressed to Andrew Hamilton, dated 1735. Gold box encloses a seal of the Freedom of the City and engraved with the Arms of the City of New York. Both items were retained in the Hamilton family, and as of 1922 were in the collection of Miss Lena Cadwallader Evans, a direct descendant. Image shows a document and two gold boxes

note-5:note_value: [Plate 149A-a] Map of Lands Included in the Central Park (etc.) 1855: Reproduction of original pen, ink, and watercolor drawing on paper by Egbert Viele, Engineer in Chief under the Commissioners of Estimate and Assessment appointed by the Supreme Court in 1853 to survey land for Central Park. Depicting the year 1855, from the collections of the City of New York, Parks Department.
